I’ve got the #WorldInMyWindow… and it’s really something. : #Apollo11InRealTime @NASA

Moon Day was July 20 1969 but #EarthDay should be every day. The Earth gives and we take 365 days a year. The least we can do is set one day apart and say “Thank You, Earth” for being so forgiving, for healing—or trying to heal—the multitude of injuries we inflict upon you daily.

I drew a calendar on the interior of Columbia during Apollo 11. I found it helpful to be able to keep track of days. Do you have any tips on how you are spending your time indoors? For more Apollo 11 graffiti, visit https://history.nasa.gov/afj/ap11fj/cm-107_graffiti.html.
Although the mission to complete the initial goal was not accomplished, #Apollo13 was deemed a “successful failure” by @NASA. Learn more here: https://go.nasa.gov/3e2i8EL
Relief! April 17 1970. The world watched as the #Apollo13 astronauts made their return to earth. : #Apollo13InRealTime
After the malfunction on #Apollo13, President Nixon received a situation report from Bill Anders and me. Read more here: https://bit.ly/2Rpnikq @NixonLibrary

On April 14 1970, the #Apollo13 malfunction was caused by an explosion and rupture of oxygen tank no. 2 in the service module. The explosion ruptured a line or damaged a valve in the no. 1 tank, causing it to lose oxygen rapidly. To read more, visit https://go.nasa.gov/34jZCmD
